In LaTeX, you can generate a table of contents automatically using the `\tableofcontents` command. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{blindtext} % Used for dummy text

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % Generates the table of contents

\section{Introduction}
\blindtext % Dummy text

\section{Background}
\subsection{Subsection 1}
\blindtext
\subsection{Subsection 2}
\blindtext

\section{Methods}
\blindtext

\section{Results}
\subsection{Subsection 1}
\blindtext
\subsection{Subsection 2}
\blindtext

\section{Discussion}
\blindtext

\section{Conclusion}
\blindtext

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to generate the table of contents automatically. The structure of the document is defined using the sectioning commands `\section` and `\subsection`.

When you compile this LaTeX document, the table of contents will be generated automatically, listing all the sections and subsections with their corresponding page numbers. The output will look something like this:

```
Contents
1 Introduction ...................................... 1
2 Background ......................................... 1
  2.1 Subsection 1 ................................... 1
  2.2 Subsection 2 ................................... 2
3 Methods ............................................ 2
4 Results ............................................ 3
  4.1 Subsection 1 ................................... 3
  4.2 Subsection 2 ................................... 3
5 Discussion ......................................... 4
6 Conclusion ......................................... 4
```

Note that the `\tableofcontents` command should be placed where you want the table of contents to appear in your document, typically after the `\begin{document}` command and before the main content.

You can customize the appearance and depth of the table of contents by using additional packages and commands. For example, the `tocloft` package provides options to modify the formatting and styling of the table of contents.

To draw a chessboard with a specific state represented by a FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) in LaTeX, you can use the `skak` package. Here's an example LaTeX code that includes the required commands and packages:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{skak}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\begin{document}

% Define custom piece colors
\definepiece{bK}{%
