}
\definepiece{wN}{%
  \fontfamily{cmr}\selectfont
  \textcolor{white}{N}
}
\definepiece{wp}{%
  \fontfamily{cmr}\selectfont
  \textcolor{white}{P}
}

% Set the board style
\setboardstyle{tinyboard}

% Draw the chessboard with the FEN notation
\newgame
\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\end{document}
```

In this code:

1. We load the `skak` package, which provides commands for typesetting chess diagrams, and the `xcolor` package for defining custom colors.
2. We define custom piece styles for both black and white pieces using the `\definepiece` command. This allows us to customize the appearance of the pieces on the chessboard.
3. We set the board style using `\setboardstyle{tinyboard}`. You can choose other styles like `smallboard`, `normalboard`, or `bigboard` depending on your preference.
4. We use the `\newgame` command to start a new game, and then draw the chessboard with the given FEN notation using `\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}`. Replace this FEN notation with the one you want to display.

When you compile this LaTeX code, it will generate a PDF file with the chessboard drawn according to the specified FEN notation.

Note: The `skak` package provides various options and customizations for drawing chessboards. You can consult the package documentation for more advanced features and configurations.

